Headline::::
‚ÄòTehran is now free': Iranian‚Äãs‚Äã‚Äã celebrate‚Äã reformist victory online




DateTime::::2016-02-29T14:57:24+0000



<p>As reformist-backed candidates sweep to victory in <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/27/reformists-and-moderates-lead-race-in-early-election-results">Iran‚Äôs elections</a>, many voters have taken to social media to share celebratory jokes and mocking memes about the country‚Äôs conservative hardliners.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/29/reformist-backed-candidates-tehran-iran-assembly-elections">Reformist-backed candidates sweep to victory in Tehran</a> </p>

<p>‚ÄúDear citizens! Attention please, attention please: Tehran is now free,‚Äù read a message widely shared on the popular messaging app, Telegram.<br/></p>

<p>Jokes started circulating on social media on 27 February after it became clear the coalition of candidates supported by the reformists, <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/26/election-day-arrives-in-iran-with-reformists-well-organised-to-seek-gains">dubbed ‚Äúthe list of hope‚Äù</a>, was likely to take all of the capital‚Äôs 30 parliamentary seats.</p>

<p>One popular quip shared on Telegram imagined the former parliament speaker and conservative hardliner Gholam-Ali Haddad-Adel ‚Äì who eventually lost his seat ‚Äì resting his head on the legs of Iran‚Äôs supreme leader, <a class="u-underline" data-component="auto-linked-tag" data-link-name="auto-linked-tag" href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/ayatollah-ali-khamenei">Ayatollah Ali Khamenei</a>, telling him: ‚ÄúI won‚Äôt go to the parliament!‚Äù with Khamenei responding: ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt be afraid, my little one. You‚Äôll find new friends.‚Äù</p>

<p>With strong <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://telegram.org/privacy">emphasis on privacy protection and anonymity for its users</a> the Telegram app has become a popular platform for pro-reform supporters to spread their message, with <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/08/telegram-the-instant-messaging-app-freeing-up-iranians-conversations">one in four Iranian now thought to be using the service</a>.</p>

<p>One joke shared widely on the app showed the head of the Guardian Council of the Constitution, Ayatollah Ahmad Jannati, pleading: ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt push me [out]!‚Äù ‚Äì a reference to the fact that he is was languishing in 15th place on the list of assembly candidates from Tehran. </p>

<p>Other social media users alluded to the house arrest of Iranian opposition figures <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/13/mir-hossein-mousavi-photograph-emerges">Mir Hossein Musavi</a>, his wife Zahra Rahnavard, and fellow reformist cleric Mehdi Karrubi. </p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/08/telegram-the-instant-messaging-app-freeing-up-iranians-conversations">Telegram: the instant messaging app freeing up Iranians' conversations</a> </p>

<p>The three popular oppositionists were detained in February 2011 after repeatedly challenging the Iranian establishment over human rights abuses. <br/> <br/>The joke has the trio‚Äôs supporters declaring that ‚Äúif Jannati doesn‚Äôt get elected, we will take to the streets to protest and claim we‚Äôre his fans so that they put <em>him</em> under house arrest.‚Äù <br/> <br/>One of the most widespread Telegram memes showed conservative religious leader Ayatollah Makarem Shirazi declaring that it was ‚Äúharam‚Äù [forbidden] to continue counting votes.<br/> <br/>Twitter users riffed on the same theme: @KevinMiston wrote ‚ÄúIranian Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei: ‚ÄòPlease end the vote counting. Please don‚Äôt stretch it any longer‚Äô.‚Äù </p>

<p class="tweet-body" dir="rtl" lang="fa"><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/%D8%B4%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B4?src=hash">#ÿ¥ŸÖÿßÿ±ÿ¥</a> ÿ±Ÿà ÿ™ŸÖŸàŸÖ ⁄©ŸÜ€åÿØ ŸÑÿ∑ŸÅÿß! ÿ®€åÿ¥ÿ™ÿ± ÿßÿ≤ ÿß€åŸÜ ⁄©⁄òÿ¥ ŸÜÿØ€åÿØ üò≠ <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://t.co/aSsHtO9Yk8">pic.twitter.com/aSsHtO9Yk8</a></p>

<p>Others poked fun at Iran‚Äôs highest authority. A viral message lampooned the supreme leader with the text: ‚ÄúI told those opposing the system to vote. But not like this!‚Äù<br/></p>

<p>It‚Äôs now thought that a combination of reformist-backed candidates, including some moderate conservatives and independents allied with Rouhani, will outnumber the conservatives in the country‚Äôs 290-seat parliament.</p>

<p>Many social media users also recognised the role former president Mohammad Khatami played in encouraging people to vote for a list of pro-reformist and relatively moderate candidates.</p>

<p>Khatami released a video online early in the campaign period urging political activists to unite behind ‚Äúthe list of hope‚Äù. His <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=psMgpk33A60">YouTube video</a> became an instant hit and helped mobilise support ‚Äì which Twitter users were quick to acknowledge.</p>

